{
  "doc_id": "47692",
  "text": "B rief intermittent periods of ischemia and reflow, termed ischemic preconditioning (PC), have been shown to protect the myocardium against injury produced by a subsequent sustained period of ischemia. [CITATION_1] PC has been shown to significantly reduce infarct size, arrhythmias, and postischemic contractile dysfunction. We previously reported that activation of phosphatidylinositol-3-kinase (PI3-kinase) is important in PC. [CITATION_2] PI3-kinase has been reported to enhance cell survival via phosphorylation of GSK-3␤. [CITATION_3] Expression of a mutant GSK that cannot be phosphorylated blocked the antiapoptotic action of PI3-kinase. [CITATION_4] We therefore examined the role of GSK-3␤ in PC. Our results suggest that phosphor-ylation and subsequent inactivation of GSK-3␤ play an important role in the protection afforded by PC in the heart.",
